  abstract = {We investigate the environmental quenching of galaxies, especially those with stellar mass (M*)\$$<$10\^\{9.5\} M\_$\backslash$odot\$, beyond the local universe. Essentially all local low-mass quenched galaxies (QGs) are believed to live close to massive central galaxies, which is a demonstration of environmental quenching. We use CANDELS data to test \{$\backslash$it whether or not\} such a dwarf QG--massive central galaxy connection exists beyond the local universe. To this purpose, we only need a statistically representative, rather than a complete, sample of low-mass galaxies, which enables our study to \$z$\backslash$gtrsim1.5\$. For each low-mass galaxy, we measure the projected distance (\$d\_\{proj\}\$) to its nearest massive neighbor (M*\$$>$10\^\{10.5\} M\_$\backslash$odot\$) within a redshift range. At a given redshift and M*, the environmental quenching effect is considered to be observed if the \$d\_\{proj\}\$ distribution of QGs (\$d\_\{proj\}\^Q\$) is significantly skewed toward lower values than that of star-forming galaxies (\$d\_\{proj\}\^\{SF\}\$). For galaxies with \$10\^\{8\} M\_$\backslash$odot $<$ M* $<$ 10\^\{10\} M\_$\backslash$odot\$, such a difference between \$d\_\{proj\}\^Q\$ and \$d\_\{proj\}\^\{SF\}\$ is detected up to \$z$\backslash$sim1\$. Also, about 10$\backslash$\% of the quenched galaxies in our sample are located between two and four Virial Radius (\$R\_\{Vir\}\$) of the massive halos. The median projected distance from low-mass QGs to their massive neighbors, \$d\_\{proj\}\^Q / R\_\{Vir\}\$, decreases with satellite M* at \$M* $\backslash$lesssim 10\^\{9.5\} M\_$\backslash$odot\$, but increases with satellite M* at \$M* $\backslash$gtrsim 10\^\{9.5\} M\_$\backslash$odot\$. This trend suggests a smooth, if any, transition of the quenching timescale around \$M* $\backslash$sim 10\^\{9.5\} M\_$\backslash$odot\$ at \$0.5$<$z$<$1.0\$.},
