for the clustering of the lenses and distinguishes between satellite and
central galaxies. Comparison with dynamical masses from the SDSS shows a
good correlation with the lensing mass for early-type galaxies. The
correlation is less clear for late-type galaxies, possibly due to
rotation. For low luminosity (stellar mass) early-type galaxies we find
a satellite fraction of \textasciitilde{}40\% which rapidly decreases to $<$10\% with
increasing luminosity (stellar mass). The satellite fraction of the
late-types has a value in the range 0-15\%, independent of luminosity or
stellar mass. At high masses the satellite fraction is not well
constrained, which we partly attribute to the modelling assumptions. To
infer virial masses we apply simple models based on an independent
satellite kinematics analysis to account for intrinsic scatter in the
scaling relations. We find that early-types in the range 1010
