mass-to-light ratio, and find for L200 $<$ 1011
L$\odot$ a value of M200/L200 = 42
$\pm$ 10 for early-types, which increases for higher luminosities to
values that are consistent with those observed for groups and clusters
of galaxies. For late-type galaxies we find a lower value of
M200/L200 = 17 $\pm$ 9. Our measurements also
show that early- and late-type galaxies have comparable halo masses for
stellar masses M${_\ast}$ $<$ 1011
M$\odot$, whereas the virial masses of early-type galaxies are
higher for higher stellar masses. To compare the efficiency with which
baryons have been converted into stars, we determine the total stellar
